description:
The scope resolution operator `::` says **"look in this scope for this name"**.

Common uses:

- `std::cout` – use `cout` from the `std` namespace.
- `MyNamespace::Thing` – use `Thing` from `MyNamespace`.
- `ClassName::method` – define a method outside the class body.

Example with a namespace and `::`:

```cpp
namespace game {
    class Player {
    public:
        void jump();
    };
}

void game::Player::jump() {
    std::cout << "jump!\n";
}

int main() {
    game::Player p;
    p.jump();
}
```

Here:
- `game` is a namespace.
- `Player` lives inside `game`.
- `void game::Player::jump()` defines the `jump` method outside the class declaration.

---

## Your task

CBit OS wants to put some math utilities into a namespace.

- Create a namespace called `cbitmath`.
- Inside it, declare a class `Adder` with:
  - a **public** method `int add(int a, int b);` (just the declaration inside the class).
- Outside the class, **define** `Adder::add` using the full scope `cbitmath::Adder::add`.
- The method should return `a + b`.

`main` will use `cbitmath::Adder` and your `add` method.

starterCode:
#include <iostream>

// define namespace cbitmath and class Adder here

int main() {
    cbitmath::Adder adder;
    int result = adder.add(3, 4);

    if (result == 7) {
        std::cout << "[PASS]\n";
    } else {
        std::cout << "[FAIL] expected 7, got " << result << "\n";
    }
}
